{"questionId":"9461","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>This question asks you to investigate regular <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"n\">\n  <mi>n</mi>\n</math></span>-sided polygons inscribed and circumscribed&nbsp;in a circle, and the perimeter of these as <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"n\">\n  <mi>n</mi>\n</math></span> tends to infinity, to make an approximation for <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\pi \">\n  <mi>π</mi>\n</math></span>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the perimeter of a regular hexagon, of side length, <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\"> <mi>x</mi> </math></span> units, inscribed in a circle of&nbsp;radius 1 unit.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>6 equilateral triangles ⇒<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\"> <mi>x</mi> </math></span> = 1&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{P_i} = 6\"> <mrow> <msub> <mi>P</mi> <mi>i</mi> </msub> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mn>6</mn> </math></span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9461","referenceCode":"SPM.3.AHL.TZ0.1c","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Find the perimeter of a regular hexagon, of side length, x units, inscribed in a circle of radius 1 unit.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.13—Limits and L’Hopitals","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.19—Maclaurin series"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}